  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem asks for the minimum number of set bits in the product of 2023 and n. This is equivalent to finding the minimum Hamming weight of a multiple of 2023. Since 2023 is not a power of 2, we need to investigate the properties of multiples of 2023 in binary.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "helper_1",
      "instructions": "Analyze the number 2023 in binary and its prime factorization. Determine if 2023 has any specific properties related to its distance from powers of 2 or if it is coprime to 2. Specifically, check if there exists an n such that 2023*n is a power of 2 (which would make k(n)=1), or if there is a constraint that forces k(n) to be greater than 1. If k(n)=1 is impossible, investigate the possibility of k(n)=2 by checking if there exist integers a and b such that 2^a + 2^b is a multiple of 2023."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_2",
      "instructions": "Test the existence of k(n) = 2. This requires finding if there exist non-negative integers a and b (a > b) such that 2^a + 2^b is divisible by 2023. This is equivalent to checking if 2^(a-b) is congruent to -1 modulo 2023, or more generally, if 2^x is congruent to -1 modulo some factor of 2023. Since 2023 = 7 * 17^2, check the order of 2 modulo 7 and modulo 289 to see if a solution for 2^x = -1 (mod 2023) exists. If no solution exists for k(n)=2, check for k(n)=3."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent should first determine if k(n)=1 is possible (it is not, as 2023 is not a power of 2). Then, use the results from helper 1 and 2 to determine if k(n)=2 is possible by checking the modular arithmetic condition 2^x = -1 mod 2023. If helper 2 proves k(n)=2 is possible, the answer is 2. If not, the parent must evaluate the next smallest possible value for k(n)."
}

